{% block style %}regular{% endblock %}
```

## Option 2: Use Context Variables in Includes

If you need more flexibility, you can use includes with context:

```html
<!-- root.html -->
{% include style_template|default:"root-regular.html" %}
```

Then in your views, you'd set `style_template` to either "root-dashboard.html" or "root-regular.html".

## Option 3: Use Template Tags

Create a custom template tag to set the style:

```python
# templatetags/style_tags.py
from django import template

register = template.Library()

@register.simple_tag(takes_context=True)
def set_style(context, style):
    context['style'] = style
    return ''
```

Then in your templates:

```html
<!-- root-dashboard.html -->
